abcLAB

Jessi Cisewski-Kehe

January 7, 2018



This is a tutorial for getting started with Approximate Bayesian Computation (ABC) in R for the Hands-On Hierarchical Bayesian Modeling of Cosmic Populations at the 231st AAS meeting in DC. The corresponding lecture notes provides some more details and background on ABC.

Please note that the code contained in this tutorial is developed for learning ABC, not for computational efficiency (i.e.the R code below can be made more efficient).


Basic ABC Algorithm

For the observed data \(x_{\text{obs}}\) and prior \(\pi(\theta)\):

  1. Sample \(\theta_{\text{prop}}\) from prior \(\pi(\theta)\)
  2. Generate \(x_{\text{prop}}\) from forward process \(F(x \mid \theta_{\text{prop}})\)
  3. Accept \(\theta_{\text{prop}}\) if \(x_{\text{obs}}\) = \(x_{\text{prop}}\)
  4. Return to step 1


Binomial example

Lets try a simple example using Binomial data.

  • Data are a sample of 1s and 0s coming from \(Y_i \sim \text{Bern}(p)\) where \(n\) = sample size, \(p = P(Y = 1)\).

  • Likelihood is \(L(p \mid y) = {n \choose y}p^y(1 - p)^{n-y}\), where \(y = \sum_{i = 1}^ny_i\) (but we will pretend we do not know this).

We need to determine a distance function, \(\rho\). Lets use the following: \[\rho(y,x) = \frac{1}{n}\left|y - x\right|\] Hence \(\rho(y,x) = 0\) if the generated dataset \(x\) has the same number of 1s as \(y\).

Set the initial parameters

Lets begin by setting some initial parameters and generating our real observations.

set.seed(123)  # This sets the random seed in case you want to run the example and get the same results
n <- 20                           #number of observations
N <- 100                      #ABC particle sample size
true.p <- .75                   #true parameter value                                               
data <- rbinom(n,1,true.p)  #Observations               
epsilon <- 0                  #Tolerance

Pick a distance function

We define the distance function below.

rho <- function(y,x) abs(sum(y)-sum(x))/n

Hyper parameters for prior

For our prior distribution on \(p\), we will use a Uniform(0,1), which a beta distribution with parameters \(\alpha = 1\) and \(\beta = 1\) (as specified below).

alpha.hyper <- 1        #Hyper parameter
beta.hyper <- 1     #Hyper parameter

ABC code

The basic ABC algorithm for our Binomial example.

p <- numeric(N)         #"Good" proposals stored in p       
for(i in 1:N){                  
  d <- epsilon+1                    
  while(d>epsilon) {                
    proposed.p <- rbeta(1,alpha.hyper,beta.hyper)       
    x <- rbinom(n,1,proposed.p)         
    d <- rho(data,x)                
  }
  p[i] <- proposed.p                
}

Plot the resulting posterior

In this example, given the likelihood and prior specified, it turns out we can easily determine the true posterior. The true posterior follows a Beta distribution with parameters \(\alpha_{posterior} = \sum_{i=1}^nx_i + \alpha_0\) and \(\beta_{posterior} = n - \sum_{i=1}^nx_i + \beta_0\), where \(\mu_0\) and \(\sigma_0\) are the parameters selected for the prior.

grid0 <- seq(0, 1, length.out = 1000)  #define a grid
hist(p, main = paste("Tolerance: ", epsilon, ", N:", N, ", n:",n, sep = ""), nclass = 25, freq = FALSE, xlim = c(0,1))
den1 <- density(p) #computes a kernel density estimate of the ABC particles
lines(den1$x,den1$y,col = "black",lwd = 4)
abline(v = true.p, col = "red", lty = 2, lwd = 4)
lines(grid0,dbeta(grid0,sum(data)+alpha.hyper,n-sum(data)+beta.hyper),col = "blue",lwd = 4)
legend("topleft", c("True Posterior","Estimated Posterior",paste("True p: ", true.p, sep = "")), col = c("blue","black","red"), lty = c(1,1,2),lwd = 3)

Normal example

Consider a data set drawn from a Normal distribution with unknown mean, \(\mu\), and known standard deviation, \(\sigma\):

\[ \begin{align*} \mu &\sim N(\mu_0, \sigma^2_0) \nonumber \\ Y_i\mid \mu, \sigma^2 &\sim N(\mu, \sigma^2) \nonumber \end{align*} \]

Set the initial parameters

set.seed(123)
n <- 25             #number of observations
N <- 100            #particle sample size
true.mu <- 0        #true parameter value (considered unknown)
sigma <- 1      #true parameter value (considered known)
data <- rnorm(n,true.mu,sigma)  #observations

Distance function

WARNING: when you change the distance function, it is a good idea to start by running it with a larger epsilon

rho <- function(y,x) abs(sum(y)-sum(x))/n
epsilon <- 0.05 #Tolerance

Hyper parameters for prior

mu.hyper <- 0               #Hyper parameter
sigma.hyper <- 10           #Hyper parameter

ABC code

The basic ABC algorithm for our Normal example.

mu <- numeric(N)            #"Good" proposals stored in mu              
for(i in 1:N){              
  d <- epsilon +1                   
  while(d>epsilon) {                
    proposed.mu <- rnorm(1,0,sigma.hyper) #<--prior draw        
    x <- rnorm(n, proposed.mu, sigma)           
    d <- rho(data,x)                
  }
  mu[i] <- proposed.mu              
}

Plot the resulting posterior

In this example, given the likelihood and prior specified, it turns out we can easily determine the true posterior. The true posterior follows a Normal distribution with parameters \(\mu_{posterior} = (\mu_0/\sigma_0^2 + \sum_{i=1}^nx_i/\sigma^2)/(1/\sigma_0^2 + n/\sigma^2)\) and \(\sigma_{posterior} = \sqrt{1/(1/\sigma_0^2 + n/\sigma^2)}\), where \(\alpha_0\) and \(\beta_0\) are the parameters selected for the prior.

grid0 <- seq(-1, 1, length.out = 1000)
mu1 <- (mu.hyper/sigma.hyper^2 + sum(data)/sigma^2)/(1/sigma.hyper^2 + n/sigma^2) #True posterior mean
sigma1 <- sqrt(1/(1/sigma.hyper^2 + n/sigma^2))  #True posterior standard deviation
hist(mu, main = paste("Tolerance: ", epsilon, ", N:", N, ", n:",n, sep = ""), nclass = 25, freq = FALSE, xlim = c(-1,1))
den1 <- density(mu)
lines(den1$x,den1$y,col = "black",lwd = 4)
abline(v = true.mu, col = "red", lty = 2, lwd = 4)
lines(grid0,dnorm(grid0,mu1,sigma1),col = "blue",lwd = 4)
legend("topright", c("True Posterior","Estimated Posterior","True mu"), col = c("blue","black","red"), lty = c(1,1,2),lwd = 3)

  3. The distance function, \(\rho\), is currently set to be \(\rho(y,x) = |\sum_{i = 1}^n y_i - \sum_{i = 1}^nx_i|/n\). Try different distance functions to see what happens (e.g. \(\rho(y,x) = (\sum_{i = 1}^n y_i - \sum_{i = 1}^nx_i)^2/n\), KS distance with R function ks.test). What happens to the ABC-posterior? This means you will have to (1) Determine an appropriate prior distribution on \(\sigma^2\) (e.g.inverse-gamma, uniform), (2) Pick an appropriate summary statistic (hint: find a sufficient statistic for \(\sigma^2\)), (3) Set-up a 2-dimensional distance function and a 2-dimensional tolerance to account for the two summary statistics.



Normal example - sequential

Set the initial parameters

set.seed(123)
n <- 25             #number of observations
N <- 100            #particle sample size
true.mu <- 0        #true parameter value (considered unknown)
sigma <- 1      #true parameter value (considered known)
data <- rnorm(n,true.mu,sigma)  #observations

time.steps <- 10    #Here you can change the number of time steps in the sequential algorithm       
epsilon <- 1        #Starting tolerance

Distance function

WARNING: when you change the distance function, it is a good idea to start by running it with a larger epsilon

rho <- function(y,x) abs(sum(y)-sum(x))/n

Hyper parameters for prior

mu.hyper <- 0       #Hyper parameter
sigma.hyper <- 10       #Hyper parameter

ABC-Population Monte Carlo code

ABC-PMC algorithm for our Normal example

weights <- matrix(1/N,time.steps,N)         
mu <- matrix(NA,time.steps,N)
d <- matrix(NA,time.steps,N)    
for(t in 1:time.steps){ 
  print(t)
  if(t==1){
    for(i in 1:N){                  
      d[t,i] <- epsilon +1                  
      while(d[t,i]>epsilon) {               
        proposed.mu <- rnorm(1,0,sigma.hyper) #<--prior draw        
        x <- rnorm(n, proposed.mu, sigma)           
        d[t,i] <- rho(data,x)               
      }
      mu[t,i] <- proposed.mu                
    }} else{
      epsilon <- c(epsilon,quantile(d[t-1,],.75))
      mean.prev <- sum(mu[t-1,]*weights[t-1,])
      var.prev <- sum((mu[t-1,] - mean.prev)^2*weights[t-1,])
      for(i in 1:N){
        d[t,i] <- epsilon[t]+1                  
        while(d[t,i]>epsilon[t]) {  
          sample.particle <- sample(N, 1, prob = weights[t-1,])
          proposed.mu0 <- mu[t-1, sample.particle]
          proposed.mu <- rnorm(1, proposed.mu0, sqrt(2*var.prev))
          x <- matrix(rnorm(n,proposed.mu, sigma),n,1)      
          d[t,i] <- rho(data,x)             
        }
        mu[t,i] <- proposed.mu  
        mu.weights.denominator <- sum(weights[t-1,]*dnorm(proposed.mu, mu[t-1,],sqrt(2*var.prev)))
        mu.weights.numerator <- dnorm(proposed.mu,0,sigma.hyper)
        weights[t,i] <- mu.weights.numerator/mu.weights.denominator     
      }}
  weights[t,] <- weights[t,]/sum(weights[t,])
}
## [1] 1
## [1] 2
## [1] 3
## [1] 4
## [1] 5
## [1] 6
## [1] 7
## [1] 8
## [1] 9
## [1] 10

Photon-counting aperture photometry

Next we will go through an example developed by Tom Loredo for the earlier portion of this workshop.

Set the initial parameters

These parameters include specification of the selection effect, which will be a threshold that has to be achieved, n_th, for a source to make it into our sample.

The total expected number of counts coming from a source is \[ \mu(F) = \epsilon F + \epsilon B + C = \epsilon F + \nu \] where \(F\) is the photon number flux of the source, \(\epsilon\) is the exposure (area \(\times\) time), \(B\) is the background rate, and \(C\) is additive contamination (and \(\nu\) is the expected number of non-source photons, \(\epsilon B + C\)).

To guard against false detections, we can incorporate a detection threshold, \(n_{th}\), so that \(n > n_{th}\) in order for \(n\) to join the sample.

set.seed(123)
k <- 4 #k-sigma threshold for the selection effect
nu <- 9.373 # expected background contribution
n_th <- k^2*(0.5 + 0.5*sqrt(1 + 4*nu/k^2))^2
n_th
## [1] 32.00065
expo <- (32 - nu)/0.1

Define several functions

The function ecounts computes the expected number of counts from a source, \(\mu(F) = \epsilon F + \nu\), for a given flux, \(f\).

#FUNCTION:  ecounts is a function that returns the expected count for a source with dimensionless flux f
ecounts <- function(f){expo*f+nu} 
ecounts(10) #Example of function use
## [1] 2272.073

The function f_est computes a (dimensionless) flux estimate given some observed number of photons, \(n\).

#FUNCTION: Compute a (dimensionless) flux estimate, given the number of observed photons, n.
f_est <- function(n){
  out <-list()
  out$f_hat <- (n-nu)/expo
  out$sig_f <- sqrt(n)/expo
  return(out) #Returns a tuple: (f_hat, sig_f)
}

The function eta computes the detection efficiency. We will not need this for ABC, but it is included for completeness.

#FUNCTION:  Detection efficiency for sources with dimensionless flux f.
#Run ?pgamma for discussion about the lower incomplete gamma function
eta <- function(f){pgamma(expo*f + nu, n_th+1, scale = 1) }

Quick checks:

Setting \(n\) exactly equal to its expectation should give a perfect f_hat estimate.

cat('f_hat should be 1:', f_est(ecounts(1))$f_hat, ", ", f_est(ecounts(1))$sig_f,'\n')
## f_hat should be 1: 1 ,  0.06784226

Expected counts from a flux of 0.1*F_0 should be at threshold:

cat('Expected counts at f=.1 vs. thresold:', ecounts(.1), n_th)
## Expected counts at f=.1 vs. thresold: 32 32.00065

Forward model

genData provides a simulated dataset for a given \(n\), \(\alpha\), \(\beta\), and \(n_{th}\). If one does not want to include the selection effect, it can be removed from the while-loop.

Rs rpois() function has some issues if the ecounts(f) is over the machine precision; when that occurs the sample, \(n\) (nflux in the code below) is drawn from a Normal distribution instead of the Poisson.

genData <- function(n, alpha, beta, n_th){
  # n = number of sources to generate
  # alpha = power law index
  # beta = power law linear "rolling" parameter
  # n_th = selection threshold
  sig <- 1/sqrt(-beta)
  mu <- sig*(alpha + 1)
  est <- matrix(NA, nrow = n, ncol = 1)
  for(ii in 1:n){
    nflux <- 0
    while(is.na(est[ii]) | nflux < n_th){
      f <- rlnorm(1, meanlog = mu, sdlog = sig) #Flux population model
      if(ecounts(f) < (0.99*.Machine$integer.max)){
        nflux <- rpois(1, ecounts(f))   #Observed flux count (accounting for exposure and background)
      }else{
        nflux <- round(rnorm(1, ecounts(f), sqrt(ecounts(f))))
      }
      est[ii] <- f_est(nflux)$f_hat                             #Estimated flux
    }
  }
  return(est)
}

Generate observations

The `real observations are drawn here using the input values for \(alpha\) and \(beta\)

alpha0 <- -1.5 #Fiducial index
beta0 <-  -0.25  #Roll rate 
n <- 50
Yobs <- genData(n, alpha0, beta0, n_th)     #"Real" observations

Distance function

This distance function is setup to compare the mean and standard deviations of the real and simulated observations. These are not necessarily the best summaries to use; try different distances and see how the ABC posterior chanes.

WARNING: due to how the subsequent code is set up, keep at least two summaries in the distance function. If you only want to include one, then set the second to a constant.

distance.function = function(x,y, inputDist){
  d1 <- abs(mean(x) - mean(y))
  d2 <- abs(sd(x) - sd(y))
  out <- cbind(d1, d2)
  return(out)
}

Set prior distributions

We are going to considered \(\alpha\) a fixed, known, parameter so we will only specify a prior on \(\beta\).

# alphaPrior <- function(n){rcauchy(n, location = 0, scale = 1)}
betaPrior <- function(n){-rexp(n, rate = 1)}

ABC algorithm parameters

In general, Ndraws and T_Iter should be larger. Ninit is the initial number of draws from the prior in the first time step so the first tolerance(s) can be adaptively selected. This makes it easier when changing the summary statistics/distance function. Ninit should be some number greater than Ndraws, and then the Ndraws with the lowest distance are retained.

Ndraws <- 100       #Number of ABC particles for approximating the posterior
Ninit <- Ndraws*5
T_Iter <- 3
post.beta <- NULL           #"Good" proposals   
post.weights <- NULL    #Importance weights 
which.quantile <- .5        #Quantile for decreasing the tolerance sequence
ndist <- length(distance.function(rexp(n),rexp(n), inputDist)) # number of summary statistics

Adaptive Start

t_Iter <- 1
Dvals1 <- matrix(NA, nrow = Ninit, ncol = ndist)
# alphaProp1 <- numeric(Ninit)
betaProp1 <- numeric(Ninit)
for(i in 1:Ninit){
  betaProp1[i] <- betaPrior(1)
  Yprop <- genData(n, alpha0, betaProp1[i], n_th)       
  Dvals1[i,] <- distance.function(Yobs,Yprop)               
}

D0 <- rank(apply(scale(Dvals1, center = FALSE)^2,1,sum), ties.method = "random")
pickNdraws <- D0<=Ndraws
Dvals <- Dvals1[pickNdraws,]

post.beta[[t_Iter]] <- betaProp1[pickNdraws]
post.weights[[t_Iter]] <- rep(1/Ndraws, Ndraws)

post.tolSeq <- matrix(NA, nrow = T_Iter, ncol = ndist)
post.tolSeq[t_Iter, ] <- apply(Dvals, 2, max)
tolSeq <- apply(Dvals, 2, quantile, which.quantile)
cat('Original tolerance', post.tolSeq[t_Iter, ],'\n')
## Original tolerance 0.8558801 4.749386
cat('New tolerance is', tolSeq,'\n')    
## New tolerance is 0.5141645 1.152447

ABC-PMC

The importance weights are a ratio of the prior distribution for \(\beta\) and the proposal distribution used (based on the previous time steps particle system). Note that the parameter space constraint (\(\beta < 0\)) puts a constraint on the kernel used to move the particle values (a truncated normal distribution is used).

for(t_Iter in 2:T_Iter){
  print(t_Iter)
  post.beta[[t_Iter]]   <- numeric(Ndraws)
  post.weights[[t_Iter]]    <- numeric(Ndraws)
  Dvals <- matrix(NA, nrow = Ndraws, ncol = ndist)
  
  prev.draws <-  post.beta[[t_Iter-1]]
  prev.weights <- post.weights[[t_Iter - 1]]
  
  mean.prev <- sum(prev.draws*prev.weights)
  var.prev <- sum((prev.draws - mean.prev)^2*prev.weights)
  
  for(i in 1:Ndraws){   
    
    jj <- 0
    while(jj == 0) {            
      # Draw from the previous values
      index.samp <- sample(1:Ndraws, 1, prob = prev.weights)
      theta.gen <- prev.draws[index.samp]
      
      # Perturb it
      thetaProp <- rnorm(1, theta.gen, sqrt(2*var.prev))
      # Try again if beta becomes positive
      while(thetaProp > 0){
        thetaProp <- rnorm(1, theta.gen, sqrt(2*var.prev))
      }             
      betaProp <- thetaProp
      Yprop <- genData(n, alpha0, betaProp, n_th)       
      Dvals1 <- distance.function(Yobs,Yprop)   
      if(sum(Dvals1 <= tolSeq)==ndist){jj <- jj + 1}        
    }   
    post.beta[[t_Iter]][i]  <- betaProp 
    Dvals[i,] <- Dvals1 
    
    wt.numerator <- dexp(-betaProp) #Betas are negative so need to flip
    trunc.norm <- pnorm(0, prev.draws, sqrt(2*var.prev)) #Used a truncated normal to "move" the particles; this is adjustment needed for density
    wt.denominator <- sum(prev.weights*dnorm(betaProp, prev.draws, sqrt(2*var.prev))/trunc.norm)
    post.weights[[t_Iter]][i] <- wt.numerator/wt.denominator 
  }
  post.weights[[t_Iter]] <-   post.weights[[t_Iter]]/sum(post.weights[[t_Iter]])    ### Add weights
  
  post.tolSeq[t_Iter, ] <- tolSeq
  tolSeq <- apply(Dvals, 2, quantile, which.quantile)
}
## [1] 2
## [1] 3
t <- t_Iter
y <- post.beta[[t]]
hist(y, nclass = 25, probability = TRUE, xlab = expression(beta), main = "ABC Posterior", ylab = "Density")
abline(v = beta0, col = "red", lty = 2, lwd = 3)
